## Step 10 - external-stream-relay-hardening

Done
Replaced `/api/camera/stream` preparation logic in `flow.json` with a direct Node.js relay (`http` module) that pipes upstream MJPEG chunks from `<camera-host>:81/stream` straight to `msg.res` instead of buffering through the `http request` node chain.
Configured relay response headers (`multipart/x-mixed-replace`, no-cache) and lifecycle cleanup on client disconnect/timeout to keep external access on live stream path instead of dropping to capture fallback.

## Step 11 - proxy-stream-stability-tuning

Done
Reverted to the stable Node-RED stream proxy chain and tuned client proxy handling in `camera-panel.js` to avoid immediate fallback: separate longer proxy connect timeout, bounded proxy reconnect attempts, and reconnect delay before entering capture fallback.
Enabled persistent upstream socket on `cameraStreamRequest` (`persist: true`) in `flow.json` and mirrored the updated client script back into `cameraPanelJs` to keep served runtime logic in sync.

## Step 12 - external-snapshot-stream-mode

Done
Replaced multi-retry proxy MJPEG handling in `camera-panel.js` with a single 6 s proxy attempt, then a fast server-proxy snapshot loop (default 350 ms / ~3 FPS) presented as "Live über Server-Proxy (Snapshot)" so external clients always get a streaming experience even when MJPEG cannot be piped through Node-RED.
Lowered server-side `fallbackIntervalMs` to 350 in `cameraConfig` (`flow.json`) and re-synced the client into the embedded `cameraPanelJs` function so the panel reliably serves live frames from anywhere via Tailscale routes without dropping to a slow capture-fallback label.

